properties.hardCodedText: Gisele Menard was born in Haiti and, after her father died, money was tight. In 1970, Menard immigrated to the United States, reuniting with her mother and sister who had settled here years earlier. She worked in the Bronx and went to school to become a certified nursing assistant. Menard settled in Queens Village with her then-husband and children, working as a nurse at Franklin Nursing Home in Flushing, Queens. She treated her kid’s friends like they were her own children and almost everyone in Queens Village knew her, said her daughter, Christie Bruno. Menard enjoyed going out and had an eye for food and clothes, luxuries she did not have growing up, her family said. She loved going on cruises — and if you couldn’t find her on the ship, she was at the casino. She enjoyed riding roller coasters into her 60s, loved The Golden Girls and Harlequin novels and “had a hunger to live,” her daughter said. Menard moved to Florida and returned to New York City in 2019. She had early onset dementia, though was still active with a companion. Menard contracted COVID-19 at the early onset of the pandemic. She was admitted to Long Island Jewish Hospital and there was a staff shortage so Gisele’s daughter, Christie, a nurse, helped care for her mother and checked her vital signs until April 10. Gisele Menard died April 11 at the Long Island Jewish Hospital at the age of 67.

properties.hardCodedText: Juan Andres Ollarvide, from San Luis Potosí, Mexico, was one of five brothers. He immigrated to the United States in 1984 after meeting his wife, Sally, in the Cancun airport. She was trying to rent a car and he was selling transport tickets. He called her the next day and, after two dates, suggested she delay her flight home. “He said, ‘We’re getting along so well, why don’t you stay another week?’” Sally said. She did. A week later she returned to her home in Florida just long enough to pack her bags to move to Mexico. Though Ollarvide had a degree in drafting when he moved to the U.S., some of his first jobs were working at a fruit stand and as a busboy in a hotel restaurant. He eventually started his own drafting company and became an American citizen in 1999. He had been receiving cancer treatment at Memorial Sloan Kettering but was improving when he contracted COVID-19. He played golf twice a week with the same group of friends; was in a men’s tennis league; and ran his business remotely throughout his treatment. Ollarvide was a favorite at his local bar and was described as a jokester, his family said. He often used the hashtag #Juaninamillion on his social media posts, which his family and friends adopted as their own. Ollarvide died April 20 at Harlem Hospital at the age of 60. A friend stenciled #JuanInAMillion on the sidewalk in front of the hospital.
properties.hardCodedPullquote: He was a larger than life jokester who lit up every room he entered.
properties.pullquoteSource: Sally Ollarvide, Juan Andres Ollarvide’s wife

properties.hardCodedText: Lucy Nicolelis was born to Greek parents in 1929 in Astoria, where she lived almost her entire life. She was married and had two daughters. “She was a Yiayia and a friend like no other, supportive and loving,” wrote her granddaughter, Stephanie Litsas. She especially enjoyed traveling with her family, to California, Greece, London, Paris, Cairo. Nicolelis was a “self-starter,” who might have a different career, and life, altogether if she had been born in a later generation. Still, Nicolelis was unusually active, her family said; she served on the PTA board, as a translator for Greek immigrants in area hospitals and a volunteer for several causes she believed in. When her husband suddenly died in 1980, Nicolelis set up a scholarship fund in his memory. Because he was a chemist, the scholarship is awarded to an outstanding student in science at St. Demetrios Preparatory School. Today, that fund is named after both of them. Nicolelis died April 15 at the Mount Sinai Queens at the age of 90.

The oldest of six children, he grew up in Oakwood, graduated from New Dorp High School and married his high school sweetheart, Linda Filippelli. A popular figure on Staten Island, Arbeeny could also be tough; his brother, Michael Arbeeny, recalled that once, when a customer refused to pay for a fence, Arbeeny connected it to his truck and dragged it down the street. When he died on April 25, Arbeeny was living in Clove Lakes Health Care and Rehabilitation Center on Staten Island. He had diabetes and was on kidney dialysis, but, his daughter said, “He was doing fantastic.” He went from chatting on the phone with her daily to dying in just six days. Along with his daughter and brother, Michael, Arbeeny is survived by his father, Michael S. Arbeeny; siblings, Cynthia, Audrey and Ashley Arbeeny, and Darian Touhey; son-in-law, Neal Messina; and grandsons, Anthony, Nicholas and Michael Messina. His wife died in 2001.

properties.hardCodedText: A lifelong Brooklyn resident, Theresa Estelle Morris was a mother to three, a grandmother to five, and a great-grandmother to 10. After a stint working in a Brooklyn pearl factory, Morris became a homemaker after marrying John Morris, who served in the military and was from Brooklyn. While her husband worked as an NYPD officer, Morris and her three children spent the summers at the family home in upstate New York. Those days were “pure joy” for her, according to her son, William Morris. “It was so cute how happy she was to be there,” he said. “She just enjoyed it so much.” After her husband died in 2004, Morris lived in Waterford on the Bay, an assisted living home. properties.hardCodedText: Thomas Crater Jr. was an activist and entrepreneur who published and edited his own local newspaper called The New York Page. Born in Memphis, Tennessee, Crater lived in Jamaica, Queens, for more than 50 years. He worked for several major news organizations including Jet, Ebony and Black Enterprise and dreamed of starting his own business. In 1984, Crater began publishing The New York Page, a newspaper that served Jamaica, Queens. Always a free paper, The New York Page ran for more than three decades. Known by many as “TC,” Crater was a sharp dresser who never wore jeans and liked wing-tipped shoes, white shirts and bowties. Up until he became sick with COVID-19, he took care of his sister, Edna Mae; fought for improvements in his apartment building; distributed a free local paper; and served as an usher for 40 years at his church. Crater, who died April 29 at Columbia Presbyterian at the age of 75, is survived by his sister, two daughters and two grandchildren. In 2018, Crater suffered a stroke. But after he recovered, he continued to care for his sister, began volunteering at a church soup kitchen and even rode his foldable bike to the farmer’s market against doctor’s orders.

properties.hardCodedText: A lifelong Staten Islander, Louis C. Barbato Jr. was born and raised in Tomkinsville, attended Curtis High School and moved to Westerleigh in the early 1970s, where he lived until his death. After graduating high school, Barbato went into carpentry and founded his own contracting company, LJB Associates. A craftsman and designer, Barbato was nicknamed “MacGyver” by those who knew him, because “he could build or fix anything,” said his daughter, Jennifer DeMeo. After a decade running LJB, Barbato became a design contractor for a national chain of cosmetology schools. In the 1990s, he went on to join the New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development as a building inspector. Ever social, Barbato enjoyed traveling, dining out, and attending Broadway shows. He also took pleasure in teaching others woodworking and often had projects going in the homes of neighbors and friends. When he was a young man, Barbato once passed a burning house on his way to work, and made sure that everyone inside escaped. “He did whatever he could to help people, whoever it was: neighbor, friend, family member, stranger,” his daughter said. After retiring 11 years ago, Barbato took a part-time maintenance job at a funeral home, where he was most likely exposed to the novel coronavirus. Barbato died April 7 at the age of 74 at Staten Island University Hospital. He is survived by his wife of 54 years, Jean (DePete), two daughters, five grandchildren and two great-granddaughters.
properties.hardCodedPullquote: My dad’s motto was ‘family first.’ He had a tattoo of it in Italian on his wrist, ‘familia prima.’ And for him, everyone was family. He treated everyone like gold, and that’s what he got in return. It’s the greatest loss.

properties.hardCodedText: From the age of 5, James C. Thompson picked cotton with his aunt rather than attend school, leaving scars on his legs. At the age of 9, he left Williston, S.C., and moved to Brooklyn with his father. He became a star athlete, leading his high school basketball team to a championship game at Madison Square Garden. Thompson played college basketball in Kansas and, after graduating, worked at the Walt Whitman Houses, a NYCHA housing complex in Fort Greene. “He had a very deep feeling for his people, and people who were poor,” said his wife of more than 40 years, Dolores B. Thompson. Thompson, known to his students as “Mr. T or JT,” worked as a teacher in a daycare center and later in a classroom support role at PS 67 for 40 years. Often, before his shift started, he’d ride his bike from his home in Prospect Heights to Fort Greene so he could greet each child at the school breakfast program. Outside of class, Thompson loved to sing or “hit the notes,” as he’d say. He helped establish the Fort Greene Council Inc. with his mentor Sam Pinn Jr., lobbying for more Black stewardship of community institutions, namely care centers for children and seniors, and worked with Brooklyn CORE (Congress on Racial Equity). Thompson died May 17 at the Cobble Hill Care Center, after suffering from kidney failure, Alzheimer’s and finally Covid-19. His wife was by his side as he died. “I had all his music on the iPod. When visiting, I’d take a little speaker, and he would sing to it.”

She loved to sing, cook classic southern Italian food and never missed the chance to “bust chops,” even with strangers, said her nephew, Rob LeDonne. Before moving into a nursing home, Graziano’s home in Canarsie — with a disco ball hanging low in the living room — was the site of most family gatherings and holidays. properties.hardCodedText: Andreas Koutsoudakis owned Tribeca’s Kitchen and worked in Manhattan’s restaurant industry for more than 30 years. On Sept. 11, 2001, Koutsoudakis was working at Gee Whiz Diner, a restaurant he co-owned, when the Twin Towers collapsed, according to an open letter written by his son in the Tribeca Citizen. Koutsoudakis quickly turned his restaurant over to FDNY workers, who used it as an emergency rescue site for their response efforts at Ground Zero. Koutsoudakis returned home that day covered in soot from the collapsing tower, still in shock. Koutsoudakis died March 27, 2020, at a hospital on Staten Island at the age of 59, according to the Tribeca Trib.

properties.hardCodedText: A native South Carolinian, Leroy Hammett ran a barber’s shop from his apartment in the south Bronx, eventually moving it to a nearby storefront named Leroy’s Unisex. Every summer, he would host a back-to-school block party with DJ and grill, offering free haircuts to children. Hammett believed in the power of prayer and community and thought that everyone should have a second chance, his family said. He liked to mingle, and invited people to attend Little Widow's Mite Baptist Church, where he served as a deacon. Hammett also volunteered with his son, LeShawn Hammett, to coach the Penn State Wilkes-Barre basketball team, leading them to a championship in March 2019. He was a proud coach, his family said, as he talked about his players and showed off his championship ring. Hammett was caring and honest — at times, too much so, said his grandson, Chris Lewis. Lewis, who was raised by Hammett, recalls watching “The Lion King” with his grandfather years ago. After seeing Simba’s father, Mufasa, dying, Lewis turned to Hammett and asked if, one day, if he was going to die. “I’m not a lion,” he said. “No one lives forever, but I’m going to be here forever.” Hammett died March 30, 2020, at Lincoln Medical Center at the age of 71.

properties.hardCodedText: Harold John Solomon Jr., was a native Staten Islander. He and his wife, Ruth, bought and moved into her parents’ house when they got married 55 years ago. In that house, they raised their four children, and Hal instilled in his kids a sense of fairness, matching whatever they could save to buy their first cars, his family said. Yet his plan fell away when his granddaughters got their driver’s licenses, and he bought them new cars straightaway. After spending a few years in the U.S. Army out of high school, Hal spent much of his career as an MTA bus driver. The job didn't fit his temperament, as he generally had little patience and was decidedly “not a people person,” his family said. But he had other hobbies: Hal was an enthusiastic regular in the local baseball world, managing three or four teams at a time, and gave every kid “a fair shake.” Despite being frequently in and out of the hospital in the last few years of his life, he always worried more about his wife’s health than his own, his family said. He died at Richmond University Medical Center on April 8, 2020, at the age of 80.
